{"cursor":"19320","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Rhodopsin', also known as 'visual purple', is a biological pigment in\nphotoreceptor cells of the retina that is responsible for the first events in\nthe perception of light. Rhodopsins belong to the G-protein-coupled receptor\nfamily and are extremely sensitive to light, enabling vision in low-light\nconditions. Exposed to light, the pigment\nimmediately photobleaches, and it takes about 45 minutes to regenerate fully in humans.\n\nIts discovery was reported by German physiologist Franz Christian Boll in 1876.\n","linknr":1045,"url":"rhodopsin","recorded":1362567719,"links":55,"instances":["biochemistry","chemistry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["G protein coupled receptors","Sensory receptors","Biological pigments","Eye"],"headings":["Structure","Phototransduction","Rhodopsin and retinal disease","Microbial rhodopsins","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/41/Rhodopsin-transducin.png/250px-Rhodopsin-transducin.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/PBB_GE_RHO_206454_s_at_tn.png/250px-PBB_GE_RHO_206454_s_at_tn.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/94/PBB_GE_RHO_206455_s_at_tn.png/250px-PBB_GE_RHO_206455_s_at_tn.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/Bovine_rhodopsin.png/200px-Bovine_rhodopsin.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/PDB_1eds_EBI.jpg/180px-PDB_1eds_EBI.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/06/PDB_1edx_EBI.jpg/180px-PDB_1edx_EBI.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/PDB_1f88_EBI.jpg/180px-PDB_1f88_EBI.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/PDB_1gzm_EBI.jpg/180px-PDB_1gzm_EBI.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th